09159nam a22011655i 9783110925449DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20132008gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)904963986  a97831109254497 a10.1515/97831109254492doi  a(DE-B1597)56949  a(OCoLC)885389041  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090002bisacsh0481xa415qDE-10100aEvent Structures in Linguistic Form and Interpretation /ced. by Johannes Dölling, Tatjana Heyde-Zybatow, Martin Schäfer. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2013] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (531 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLanguage, Context and Cognition ,x1866-8313 ;v500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tSection I: Event Structure and Syntactic Construction -- tPatients in Igbo and Mandarin -- tEvent decomposition and the syntax and semantics of durative phrases in Chinese -- tSyntactic decomposition of events in Korean and Standard Indonesian -- tSection II. Event Structure and Modification -- tUnifying illegally -- tAdverbial modification of adjectives: Evaluatives and a little beyond -- tThe structure of criterion predicates -- tReference to embedded eventualities -- tSection III: Event Structure and Situation Aspect -- tTwo puzzles for a theory of lexical aspect: Semelfactives and degree achievements -- tThe notion of 'path' in aspectual composition: Evidence from Japanese -- tReflexive intransitives in Spanish and event semantics -- tScalar complexity and the structure of events -- tSection IV: Event Structure and Plurality -- tOn the plurality of verbs -- tEvent quantifícation and distributivity -- tThe event structure of irreducibly symmetric reciprocals -- tExistential readings for bare plurals in object position -- tSection V: Event Structure and Temporal Location -- tTense and adverbial quantification -- tPhase structures and quantification -- tCohesion in temporal context: The role of aspectual adverbs -- tMandarin sentential -le, perfect and English already -- tSection VI: Event Structure and Natural Language Ontology -- tThe lower part of event ontology -- tVerbs of creation -- tShort Portraits of the Authors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDieser Band befasst sich mit dem Problem, wie konzeptuelle Information über Ereignisstrukturen in der Sprache ausgedrückt und im Interpretationsprozess rekonstruiert wird. Die in ihm versammelten Beiträge präsentieren wichtige neue Einsichten aus der gegenwärtigen semantischen und syntaktischen Forschung zu diesem Gegenstand. Im Einzelnen werden folgende Problembereiche behandelt: Ereignisstruktur und syntaktische Konstruktion, Ereignisstruktur und Modifikation, Ereignisstruktur und Plural, Ereignisstruktur und temporale Beziehung, Ereignisstruktur und Situationsaspekt sowie Ereignisstruktur und Sprachontologie. Hervorzuheben ist, dass die Thematik nicht nur anhand des Englischen und Deutschen, sondern auch anhand von anderen Sprachen wie dem Mandarin, Japanischen, Koreanischen, Indonesischen und Igbo diskutiert wird. Der Band liefert damit einen überzeugenden Beleg für die empirische Fruchtbarkeit von ereignisbasierten Analysen.  aThis volume addresses the problem of how language expresses conceptual information on event structures and how such information can be reconstructed in the interpretation process. The papers present important new insights into recent semantic and syntactic research on the topic. The volume deals with the following problems in detail: event structure and syntactic construction, event structure and modification, event structure and plurality, event structure and temporal relation, event structure and situation aspect, and event structure and language ontology. Importantly, the topic is discussed not only on the basis of English and German but on the basis of other languages including Mandarin, Japanese, Korean, Indonesian, and Igbo as well. This volume thus provides solid evidence towards clarifying the empirical use of event based analyses.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aLinguistics and SemioticsxTheoretical Frameworks and DisciplinesxLinguistics, other. 0aPhilosophyxPhilosophy, other. 4aAdverb. 4aEreignis. 4aVerbalaspekt. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aAdverbs.  aEvents.1 aBeavers, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDimitriadis, Alexis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDölling, Johannes, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEckardt, Regine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgg, Markus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEndriss, Cornelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGao, Meijia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlasbey, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeyde-Zybatow, Tatjana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHinterwimmer, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKratzer, Angelika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLin, Jo-wang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalink, Marko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCready, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeulen, Alice G. Β. ter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorzycki